\f0\b\fs48 \cf2 \strokec2 Feature 2: "Omni-Gaze" \'97 Contextual Multi-Stage Violation & Perspective-Corrected OCR Pipeline
\f1\fs36 \cf0 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs37\fsmilli18667 \cf2 \strokec2 The Concept
\f1\fs28 \cf0 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \strokec2 A basic YOLO bounding-box implementation is insufficient for the chaotic and densely packed nature of Indian traffic. Detecting a "person" and a "motorcycle" in a frame does not automatically equate to a triple-riding violation, nor does detecting a "helmet" mean the rider is actually wearing it securely. Furthermore, evaluating red-light violations or wrong-side driving requires temporal tracking across multiple frames, not just static object detection.
\f3\fs24 \cf0 \strokec3 \

\f2\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \strokec2 "Omni-Gaze" introduces a hierarchical relational network atop the newly released YOLOv12 architecture, combined with deterministic OpenCV geometric unwarping and Transformer-based Optical Character Recognition (TrOCR). YOLOv12 is selected for its Attention-Centric (A2) framework and Residual Efficient Layer Aggregation Networks (R-ELAN), which drastically outperform older YOLO versions in crowded, multi-class environments while maintaining edge-deployment latency
\fs19\fsmilli9600 \cf4 \super \strokec4 19
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \nosupersub \strokec2 . The system identifies motorcycles, riders, helmets, seatbelts, traffic lights, and license plates. It then utilizes specific algorithms to classify complex violations.
\f3\fs24 \cf0 \strokec3 \

\f2\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \strokec2 For license plate extraction, standard OCR engines like Tesseract frequently fail when faced with the skewed, warped, or partially obscured license plates typical of Indian roadways. Omni-Gaze utilizes an OpenCV algorithmic layer to find the four corners of a skewed plate, applies a perspective transform to flatten it
\fs19\fsmilli9600 \cf4 \super \strokec4 22
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \nosupersub \strokec2 , and passes the normalized, high-resolution crop to a Vision Transformer (TrOCR). Unlike CNN-based OCR that struggles with sequential context, the TrOCR uses a vision encoder to extract image features and a sequence-to-sequence decoder to generate the text string, significantly reducing the character error rate
\fs19\fsmilli9600 \cf4 \super \strokec4 24
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \nosupersub \strokec2 .
\f3\fs24 \cf0 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs37\fsmilli18667 \cf2 \strokec2 How it Solves the Sponsor's Pain Point
\f1\fs28 \cf0 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \strokec2 The primary failure point of traditional ANPR systems in Bengaluru is the high error rate on slanted or non-standard license plates, resulting in incorrect challans being mailed to innocent citizens
\fs19\fsmilli9600 \cf4 \super \strokec4 8
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \nosupersub \strokec2 . This generates massive public backlash and requires TMC operators to manually review dispute tickets. By flattening the plate via OpenCV before OCR, and by using a Transformer model that reads whole sequences, Omni-Gaze achieves near-perfect accuracy
\fs19\fsmilli9600 \cf4 \super \strokec4 22
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \nosupersub \strokec2 . Furthermore, the hierarchical mapping logic prevents false positives\'97such as flagging a pedestrian walking behind a motorcycle as a "triple rider"\'97ensuring that every generated alert is actionable and legally sound without requiring human verification.
\f3\fs24 \cf0 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs37\fsmilli18667 \cf2 \strokec2 The Visual/Frontend Component
\f1\fs28 \cf0 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \strokec2 To effectively demonstrate this backend complexity, Omni-Gaze will be showcased via an "Exploded Relational View" on the React.js dashboard.
\f3\fs24 \cf0 \strokec3 \

